# Project Cursor Rules — AI360

## General

- Always refer to the PRD at docs/PRD.md for feature requirements and acceptance criteria before implementing.
- Always refer to docs/architecture.md for the microservices architecture, service boundaries, data ownership, inter-service communication, and event catalog.
- Follow the project's existing patterns and conventions when adding new code.
- Write clear, self-documenting code. Avoid unnecessary comments that just restate what the code does.

## Microservices Architecture

- The system is decomposed into 10 microservices: API Gateway, User Service, Organization Service, Ingestion Service, Knowledge Engine, Intelligence Service, Notification Service, Credit Service, Export Service, Pipeline Orchestrator.
- Each service owns its data store (database-per-service). Never query another service's database directly — use internal REST APIs or events.
- Synchronous REST calls for query-time reads; asynchronous events (Redis Streams) for pipeline orchestration and cross-service coordination.
- All inter-service REST calls use internal JWT authentication (cluster-internal signing key).
- Every service must expose `/health/live` and `/health/ready` endpoints for Kubernetes probes.
- Use the event envelope format defined in docs/architecture.md. Always include `correlation_id` in events and propagate it via `X-Correlation-ID` header.
- Pipeline stages must be idempotent — processing the same event twice must produce the same result.
- External dependency calls (LLM, data source APIs, notification providers) must use the circuit breaker pattern.
- Service-specific code lives in its own top-level directory (e.g., `services/user-service/`, `services/org-service/`). Shared libraries live in `libs/`.

## Tech Stack

- Backend: Python 3.10+ with FastAPI.
- Frontend: React 18 with TypeScript.
- Styling: Tailwind CSS. Do not use inline styles.
- State management: Use React hooks and context. Only introduce Redux if complexity demands it.
- Relational database: PostgreSQL with SQLAlchemy ORM. No raw SQL queries.
- Knowledge graph & vector store: Neo4j via the official Python driver. Use Neo4j's native vector index for embedding storage and similarity search.
- Background tasks: Celery with Redis as the message broker for scraping and analysis pipelines.
- AI/LLM: Use a provider-agnostic abstraction layer so the LLM can be swapped without code changes. Default provider is Anthropic (Claude). All LLM calls must go through the abstraction layer (never call a specific provider SDK directly). Provider and model are read from PlatformSettings at runtime.
- Agentic AI: Use LangGraph for the Annual Report processing pipeline. Each agent should be independently testable. Use LangGraph's stateful graph execution for multi-step workflows.
- Embeddings: The embedding model is configurable via a provider-agnostic interface. Default is self-hosted BGE-M3 (BAAI, 1024-dim). All embedding calls must go through the abstraction layer (never call a specific provider directly). Store embeddings in Neo4j's native vector index. Vector dimensions are read from config, not hardcoded.

## Code Style

- Python: Follow PEP 8. Use type hints for all function signatures.
- TypeScript: Use strict mode. Prefer interfaces over type aliases for object shapes.
- React: Use functional components with hooks. No class components.
- Naming: Use snake_case for Python, camelCase for TypeScript variables/functions, PascalCase for React components and TypeScript interfaces.

## API Design

- RESTful endpoints following the patterns defined in docs/PRD.md and docs/architecture.md.
- All API responses use a consistent envelope: { "data": ..., "error": null } or { "data": null, "error": { "message": "..." } }.
- Validate all request inputs using Pydantic models (backend).
- Internal service-to-service APIs live under `/internal/` and are not routed through the API Gateway. They use internal JWT auth.
- The API Gateway handles all external-facing routing, SSO authentication, RBAC enforcement, rate limiting, and CORS.

## Data Ingestion & Scraping

- All web scraping must respect robots.txt directives of target sites.
- Only ingest publicly available, non-paywalled content (unless using a paid data source with proper licensing).
- Scraping tasks run as Celery background jobs, never in the request/response cycle.
- Scraping frequency is admin-configurable per organization (stored in Organization.scraping_frequency). Read from DB, never hardcode intervals.
- Financial and news data sources use a pluggable adapter pattern. All data source calls must go through the adapter interface (never call a specific API directly). New sources are added via DataSourceConfig, not code changes.
- Deduplicate news articles by source URL before storing. When multiple sources return the same data, merge by priority order.
- News articles have a 7-year retention policy (retention_expires_at = published_at + 7 years). A scheduled job handles archival/purge. Financial snapshots, analysis reports, Annual Reports, knowledge graph data, and embeddings are persisted indefinitely — never delete them.

## Testing

- Write unit tests for all new backend modules using pytest.
- Write component tests for React components using React Testing Library.
- Acceptance criteria from the PRD should map to test cases.

## Security & RBAC

- All endpoints require authentication via corporate SSO.
- Role-based access control (RBAC) is enforced at the API layer using FastAPI dependencies. Three roles: Admin, Analyst, Viewer.
- Use a reusable dependency (e.g., `require_role("admin")`) to protect endpoints. Never check roles with ad-hoc logic.
- The frontend must hide or disable UI elements based on the user's role (fetched via GET /api/me at session start).
- Sanitize all user inputs before processing.
- Never log sensitive data (tokens, passwords, PII).
- Never store proprietary or paywalled content (unless sourced from a licensed paid data provider).

## Notifications

- All notifications must go through the notification dispatcher service. Never send emails/SMS/push directly from business logic.
- In-app notifications are always created. Email, SMS, and push delivery depend on the user's NotificationPreferences.
- Respect quiet hours — queue non-critical notifications during quiet hours and deliver when they end.
- Log delivery status per channel for every notification.

## Credits & Billing

- All billable actions (analysis requests, exports, AI Q&A queries) must check credit balance and quota before execution. Never debit credits after the action — always check and reserve first.
- Credit pricing is read from the CreditPricing table at runtime, never hardcoded.
- Quota limits are enforced at the API layer. Return a clear 402/403 response when credits are insufficient or quota is reached.
- Credit balance must never go negative. Use database-level constraints or transactions to ensure atomicity.
